04948nam a22006615i 9781846158766DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20102010xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461587667 a10.1515/97818461587662doi  a(DE-B1597)675536  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aVK1491 7aHIS0370302bisacsh04a364.1641 aPearce, Cathryn J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCornish Wrecking, 1700-1860 :bReality and Popular Myth /cCathryn J. Pearce. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (278 p.) :b13 line illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFigures, Maps and Tables -- tPreface and Acknowledgements -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: A Reputation for Wrecking -- t1 Cornwall and the Sea -- t2 ‘Dead Wrecks’ and the Foundation of Wreck Law -- t3 Wrecking and Criminality -- t4 The Cornish Wrecker -- t5 Wrecking and Popular Morality -- t6 Wrecking and Enforcement of the Law -- t7 Lords of the Manor and their Right of Wreck -- t8 Wrecking and Centralised Authority -- t9 The Wrecker, the Press, and the Pulpit -- tConclusion: Myths and Reputations Reconsidered -- tAppendices -- tAppendix 1 Wreck Bills and Statutes, 1700–1854 -- tAppendix 2 Cornish Wreck Returns, Constabulary Report 1837 -- tAppendix 3 Presentments, Manor of Connerton, 1704–59 -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShows how the image of Cornish wreckers as villains deliberately luring ships on to the rocks is a myth.Although the popular myth of Cornish wrecking is well-known within British culture, this book is the first comprehensive, systematic inquiry to separate out the layers of myth from the actual practices. Weaving in legal, social and cultural history, it traces the development of wreck law - the right to salvage goods washed on shore - and explores the responses of a coastal populace who found their customary practices increasingly outside the law, especially as local individual rights were being curtailed and the role of centralised authority asserted. This groundbreaking study also considers the myths surrounding wrecking, showing how these developed over time, and how moral attitudes towards wrecking changed. Overall, the picture of evil wreckers deliberately luring ships onto the rocks is dispelled, to be replaced by a detailed picture of a coastal populace - poor and gentry alike - who were involved in a multi-faceted, sophisticated coastal practice and who had their own complex popular beliefs about the harvest and salvage of goods washing ashore from shipwreck. CATHRYN J. PEARCE holds a PhD in Maritime History from Greenwich Maritime Institute. A former associate professor of history with the University of Alaska Anchorage's Kenai Peninsula College, she is now with University Campus Suffolk where she continues to research on the relationship of coastal people with the sea.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSalvagezEnglandzCornwall (County)xHistoryy18th century. 0aSalvagezEnglandzCornwall (County)xHistoryy19th century. 0aShipwreckszEnglandzCornwall (County)xHistoryy18th century. 0aShipwreckszEnglandzCornwall (County)xHistoryy19th century. 0aWreckers (Plunderers of ships)xHistoryy18th century. 0aWreckers (Plunderers of ships)xHistoryy19th century. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Modern / General.2bisacsh  aCornish coast.  aCornish wreckers.  acoastal populace.  acustomary practices.  aharvest.  apopular beliefs.  asalvage of goods.  ashipwrecks.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package p